  "opinion": "As an 85-year-old woman living in Rome, retired and spending several hours daily on social media, I have seen how technology has evolved, and with it, the spread of fake content. My perspective on managing this issue is shaped by my life experiences, my curiosity, and my religious beliefs in Islam, which emphasize truth and integrity. I approach social media with a cautious yet engaged mindset, given my low openness to new experiences but high conscientiousness, which makes me diligent in verifying information. First, I believe in taking personal responsibility. When I come across suspicious posts, especially those related to health, politics, or community events, I do not share them impulsively. Instead, I take time to cross-check with reliable sources, such as official news outlets or trusted community leaders in my local mosque. This aligns with my conscientious nature, as I value accuracy and order in my daily life, much like how I tend my garden or bake with precise recipes. Second, I use social media features to my advantage. I report fake content when I encounter it, as this helps platforms identify and remove harmful material. My low extraversion means I prefer quiet, thoughtful interactions online, so I often engage in private messages with friends and family to discuss concerns rather than posting publicly. This reduces the spread of misinformation in my circles. Third, I rely on my hobbies, like painting and hiking, to ground myself in reality. These activities remind me of the beauty and truth in the physical world, which contrasts with the sometimes deceptive nature of online content. My moderate neuroticism makes me aware of the anxiety fake news can cause, so I limit my exposure by setting specific times for social media use, ensuring it does not overwhelm my peace of mind. In dealing with fake content, I also draw on my Islamic faith, which teaches the importance of honesty and protecting others from harm. I encourage my children and grandchildren to be critical thinkers online, sharing stories from my past to illustrate how misinformation can lead to real-world consequences. Ultimately, managing fake content requires a blend of personal vigilance, community support, and a balanced lifestyle. By staying informed yet skeptical, and by fostering genuine connections offline, we can navigate social media more safely and responsibly.",
